      id: "origin-ii-bansi-iksha-bhima",
      name: "ORIGIN II — Bansi (Iksha Bhima)",
      era: "Srinagar to Multan, late 9th century",
      blurb: "Iksha, thirteenth child and fifth daughter of the Raja Kanishka of Sonapura in Srinagar, is confined to embroidery and the marriage market while her brothers learn statecraft. She steals her education by impersonating her brother Vikrahma in lessons, befriending the servant boy Ravi, and slipping through the city as one of the invisible servants. When she overhears that her father and uncle plan to sell her as the sixth wife of the fifty-three-year-old Shahi, she walks out the palace gate disguised as Ravi, abandons the name Iksha Bhima for 'Bansi' (flute), and joins a westward-bound caravan as a stable hand. In Multan she cracks the locks of a wine-shop run by Dalir and is inducted into the Bahn-Sa-Sahn — a sprawling guild of thieves, healers, and fixers — where she trains for two years under the combat-instructor Arjun, learning locks, disguise, and the sickle as her signature weapon. Her first solo job exposes her to a cache of warm green-stone idols and a dried child's face in a sealed box, residues that mark her hands and become the guild's reason to begin her next phase of training. She leaves Multan with fine daggers and razor-wire, works west as a thief and ship's-hand, and joins the Yemeni captain Darooq's dhow with the sailor Tarek.",
