      blurb: "Hind's caravan reaches the oasis of Merv and the company scatters into the city's pleasures and tasks. Lüèduó is pulled from a dancer's tent into a vision of the Nagini, who calls him a liar and warns that what is coming still hunts them and that he owes her a debt. At dusk a half-dead Turkic girl, Earmack, gallops in on a stolen horse with news of a kurgan-cult: walking-wolves led by Karishkir, three hundred years old, with three lovers — Nizack the sorcerer, Drekhlo 'dragon-claw,' and Revna the Nightwolf Huntress — in service to a great chieftain called Ahad, the Khan of the Nine Skulls. Bansi and Lüèduó pry the drunk Sadia out of Arazu's wineshop while the others escort Earmack to Abu-Rayhan's house, where the scholar identifies Karishkir as a three-hundred-year-old queen and the kurgan ritual as an attempt to raise an ancient dead. A werewolf descends on Eskil and Giovanni in the streets; Giovanni kills it with a thrust through the heart, naming 'Karishkir' with its dying word. Abu-Rayhan supplies silver and naphtha and the company rides into the steppe with Earmack as guide. At the ravine above the kurgan a psychic howling drops Bansi and Eskil to their knees bleeding from nose and ears; Karishkir's voice rings out: 'Flay them, my darlings.'",
